      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: LED Architect Desk Lamp with Clamp</h2>
      <p>This clamp-mounted architect lamp won on the metric that matters most for a work desk: it gave us full lighting control while occupying zero desk surface. Traditional base lamps eat six to eight inches of precious desk depth, which on a 24-inch-deep desk means giving up a quarter of your usable workspace. The clamp mounts to the back edge in under a minute, and the gooseneck arm reaches 24 inches forward to position light exactly where you need it without casting monitor glare.</p>
      <p>The three color modes are genuinely useful, not a gimmick. According to manufacturer specifications, the modes are 2700K (warm), 4000K (neutral), and 5500K (cool), each accurate to within 200 Kelvin — far more accurate than the randomly labeled modes on cheaper lamps. For daytime screen work we recommend 4000K neutral, which is bright enough to stay alert but does not create the harsh reflective glare that 6500K cool white produces on glossy monitors. The ten brightness levels span from a dim nightlight glow to a full 800 lux at desk center, more than enough for detail work.</p>
      <p>The LED strip design is what sets this apart from single-bulb lamps. Instead of a concentrated point of light that creates hot spots and harsh shadows, the strip spreads illumination evenly across a 20-inch wide swath of desk. According to manufacturer specifications, lux variation is less than 15% across the keyboard and mouse area, compared to 60% variation with a traditional bulb lamp. USB powering means no bulky wall brick competing for outlet space, and you can plug it directly into a monitor or hub. The one weakness: the gooseneck can droop slightly at full extension, so position the heaviest part of the arm closer to the clamp.</p>

