      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: IKEA TERTIAL Work Lamp</h2>
      <p>If you want to spend under $20 and do not need dimming or color modes, the IKEA TERTIAL is the classic value pick. It uses a standard E26 bulb socket, so you can pair it with any LED bulb you choose — warm for reading, daylight for work. The spring-loaded arm holds position well and the clamp is sturdy enough for everyday use. With a 60W-equivalent LED bulb, expected output is approximately 450 lux at desk center, adequate for general office work.</p>
      <p>The tradeoffs are real. There is no built-in dimming or color control unless you buy a smart bulb separately, the arm is shorter than the architect lamp so coverage is narrower, and the single-bulb design creates more shadow variation across the desk. For a budget secondary lamp or a reading nook, it is hard to beat. For a primary work lamp used eight hours a day, the extra $20 for the clamp LED with dimming is worth it.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first decision is clamp versus base. If your desk is under 30 inches deep or you use dual monitors, get a clamp lamp — the reclaimed surface space matters more than any feature on a base lamp. Clamp lamps also let you position the light source behind and above your monitor, which is the optimal angle for reducing screen glare. Base lamps make sense only for large desks, reading chairs, or situations where you cannot clamp to an edge.</p>
      <p>Color temperature control is the feature most people underestimate. A single 6500K cool white lamp is fine for a warehouse but creates fatigue and glare in an office. Look for a lamp with at least three modes, and verify the claimed Kelvin with reviews if possible — many cheap lamps claim 4000K but actually output closer to 5500K. For sustained screen work, 4000K neutral white is the sweet spot. Use 2700K warm for the last two hours of the evening to avoid suppressing melatonin.</p>
      <p>Finally, check the light distribution, not just total lumens. A 1000-lumen point source creates harsh shadows and hot spots that fatigue your eyes as your pupils constantly adjust. An LED bar or panel that spreads light evenly across the work surface is far more comfortable than a higher-lumen single bulb. If you cannot test in person, look for "edge-lit" or "side-emitting" designs, which distribute light more uniformly than direct-emitting LEDs.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>What color temperature is best for screen work?</summary>
          <p>For computer work, 4000K (neutral white) is the sweet spot. It is bright enough to keep you alert but not as harsh as 6500K cool white, which can increase screen glare. Reserve 2700K warm light for evening reading and 5000K+ for detail tasks like soldering.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Is a clamp desk lamp better than a base lamp?</summary>
          <p>For small desks and dual-monitor setups, yes. A clamp lamp frees up 6-8 inches of desk depth that a base would occupy, and the longer reach lets you position light behind your monitor to reduce screen glare. Base lamps are fine for large desks or reading nooks.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How many lumens do I need for a desk lamp?</summary>
          <p>For general office work, 450-800 lumens is sufficient. For detailed tasks like drafting or electronics, aim for 1000+ lumens. Avoid anything above 1500 lumens pointed at a screen, as it will create reflective glare that strains your eyes more than the darkness would.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

